   <abstract>Throughout recent years, the Internet of Things (IoT) has grown rapidly. A concept called Fog Computing (FC) has been developed in response to IoT demands for the processing of massive volumes of data and the availability of substantial computational resources. In order to eliminate network latency, FC attempts to bring the computation resources closer to the IoT devices. An essential part of FC is an offloading mechanism, which can be utilized to make the most efficient use of FC nodes, especially when dealing with applications that require high throughput and low latency. In general, offloading policies can be classified as centralized or decentralized. Because of the growing number of IoT devices, which results in the expansion of the FC layer beyond the initial configurations, centralized scheduling solutions for time-sensitive tasks face two significant challenges: first, increasing complexity, and second, non-fault tolerating. To address these issues, scalable decentralized/distributed approaches have been developed to schedule tasks through the autonomous collaboration of a small number of nodes (neighbors). However, designing algorithms that make optimal decisions is difficult without a thorough understanding of the network or nodes' state. This paper presents a scalable algorithm for offloading time-sensitive tasks through a semi-network aware distributed scheduling mechanism. Based on the evaluation results obtained for acceptance rate, response time, and network resource usage, the proposed method outperforms the state-of-the-art on average.</abstract>
